const a = [
  {"id":6483,"text":"Which of the following conditions is characterized by a spike and dome appearance of the glomerular basement membrane on electron microscopy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 913.","responses":[{"text":"Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Minimal change disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous glomerulonephritis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":6967,"text":"A dead body of a girl was brought for autopsy. On examination, she was pregnant, and severe injuries were observed in her pelvic area. On inquiry, her mother told that she tried to criminally induce abortion during which she died within minutes. What is the most probable cause of death?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 340.","responses":[{"text":"Secondary hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peritonitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagal inhibition","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal Failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7093,"text":"Anatomical waste should be disposed off in which color-coded bag?","explanation":null,"reference":"Janani, K., and Mahalakshmi Jayaraman. “Knowledge, Awareness, and Practice of Biomedical Waste Segregation in a Dental Office.” Journal of Advanced Pharmaceutical Technology \u0026 Research, vol. 13, no. Suppl 1, Nov. 2022, p. S1. www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov, https://doi.org/10.4103/japtr.japtr_231_22.","responses":[{"text":"Yellow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Red","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"White","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Black","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7610,"text":"A 30-year-old unmarried woman came to a doctor and requested her to induce an abortion. The doctor refused and told the women there is severe punishment for criminal abortion in Pakistan. What is the punishment of criminal abortion before babies' organs are formed in Pakistan?","explanation":null,"reference":"Pakistan’s abortion provisions. Center for Reproductive Rights. Accessed November 3, 2022. https://reproductiverights.org/maps/provision/pakistans-abortion-provisions/","responses":[{"text":"Full diyat of the child","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3 years imprisonment if with consent","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1/20 diyat of the child","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7 years imprisonment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3 years imprisonment if without consent","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8041,"text":"In Pakistan, on which grounds is abortion justifiable?","explanation":null,"reference":"“Pakistan’s Abortion Provisions.” Center for Reproductive Rights, https://reproductiverights.org/maps/provision/pakistans-abortion-provisions/. Accessed 17 Nov. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Humanitarian grounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eugenic grounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Therapeutic grounds","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Threatened","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Social grounds","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8100,"text":"A graduate student is planning to make a high-altitude climb in South America while on vacation. He will not have time to acclimate slowly to the altitude. What drug is useful in preventing high-altitude sickness?","explanation":null,"reference":"Paralikar, Swapnil J., and Jagdish H. Paralikar. “High-Altitude Medicine.” Indian Journal of Occupational and Environmental Medicine, 2010, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2923424/.","responses":[{"text":"Acetazolamide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Desmopressin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amiloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Demeclocycline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethacrynic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13733,"text":"A 60-year-old patient has a clinical history of frequent episodes of renal colic with calcium-containing stones. His clinical workup indicates that he has a defect in proximal tubular calcium reabsorption. Which of the following diuretic agent is most useful in the treatment of recurrent calcium stones?","explanation":"Thiazide diuretics, like **chlorthalidone**, are known to decrease the urinary excretion of calcium by promoting its reabsorption in the distal convoluted tubule of the nephron. This reduction in urinary calcium excretion can help **prevent** the formation of **calcium-containing kidney stones**, particularly those associated with hypercalciuria.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSpironolactone is a potassium-sparing diuretic and is not typically used for the prevention of calcium stones. It is more commonly used in conditions where potassium retention is desired.\r\n\r\nDiazoxide is primarily used to treat certain medical conditions, such as hypoglycemia and hypertensive emergencies.\r\n\r\nMannitol is an osmotic diuretic used to increase urine output and reduce intracranial or intraocular pressure. \r\n\r\nEthacrynic acid is a loop diuretic used for conditions like edema and heart failure.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 138.","responses":[{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mannitol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diazoxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorthalidone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethacrynic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21615,"text":"A 60-year-old man seeks medical attention because of recurrent urinary tract\r\ninfections. The patient has a history of increasing difficulty in\r\nurination, decreased flow, straining, and hesitancy over the last several\r\nmonths. Prostate-specific antigen (PSA) level is mildly elevated and a\r\nprostate biopsy proves benign. Which of the following is the most appropriate\r\ninitial management of this patient with benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH)?","explanation":"Benign prostatic hyperplasia is a common condition in aging men that can lead to lower urinary tract symptoms (LUTS) due to an enlarged prostate gland. **Alpha-adrenergic blockers,** such as tamsulosin or alfuzosin, help relax the smooth muscle in the prostate and bladder neck, improving urine flow and relieving symptoms like hesitancy, straining, and incomplete voiding. These medications can provide relatively rapid relief of symptoms.\r\n\r\nWhile 5-alpha reductase inhibitors like finasteride or dutasteride can also be used to treat BPH, they are typically considered for patients with larger prostates and are not the first-line choice for patients with recurrent urinary tract infections and moderate symptoms.\r\n\r\nSurgical options like transurethral resection of the prostate (TURP) or open prostatectomy are considered when medical management is ineffective or in severe cases, but they are not the initial management of choice.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 438.","responses":[{"text":"Transurethral resection of the prostate (TURP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha adrenergic blocker","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"5-Alpha reductase inhibitor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha adrenergic blocker and 5-alpha reductase inhibitor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Open prostatectomy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21616,"text":"A 55-year-old man presents with fever and pain in the perineal region. Upon\r\nfurther questioning, he also complains of frequency, urgency, dysuria, and a\r\ndecreased urinary stream. On physical examination his abdomen Is soft, non-distended, and non-tender, Digital  Rectal examination (DRE) demonstrates exquisite\r\ntenderness on the anterior aspect. Laboratory investigation reveals\r\nleukocytosis and findings on urinalysis are consistent with a bacterial\r\ninfection. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Acute bacterial prostatitis** typically presents with sudden onset symptoms such as fever, chills, perineal or pelvic pain, dysuria, frequency, and urgency. Digital Rectal Examination (DRE) often reveals tenderness on the anterior aspect of the prostate gland.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 437.","responses":[{"text":"Pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Benign prostatic hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrolithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinary tract infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21617,"text":"A 36-year-old man presents to the emergency room with renal colic. His vital\r\nsigns are normal and a urinalysis shows microscopic hematuria. A radiograph\r\nreveals a 1.6 cm stone. Which of the following Is the most appropriate\r\nmanagement of this patient?","explanation":"**Extracorporeal shock wave lithotripsy (ESWL)** is a non-invasive procedure that uses shock waves to break down kidney stones into smaller fragments, making it easier for them to pass naturally through the urinary tract. It is the preferred treatment for most uncomplicated renal stones that are **between 5 mm and 2 cm in size.** \r\n\r\nHydration and analgesics are essential for symptom relief and can help facilitate stone passage. Alpha adrenergic blockers may be considered to relax the smooth muscles in the ureter and aid stone passage, but they are often reserved for cases where the stone is not amenable to ESWL or if there are contraindications to ESWL.\r\n\r\nOpen surgery and percutaneous nephrostomy tube placement are more invasive options and are typically reserved for complex cases or situations where other treatments have failed.","reference":"Agabegi SS, Agabegi ED, Duncan MD, Chuang K. Step-Up to Medicine. 6th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2024: 294.","responses":[{"text":"Percutancous nephrostomy tube","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydration and analgesics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Open surgery to remove the stone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha adrenergic blocker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extracorporeal lithotripsy","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21618,"text":"A 32-year-old man presents with an asymptomatic mass in his right testicle. On examination, the mass cannot be transilluminated. Ultrasound shows a solid mass in the right testicle. Which of the following is the most accurate method in obtaining a diagnosis of testicular cancer?","explanation":"For a solid mass in the testicle, the initial diagnostic approach often involves serum tumor marker analysis, including the measurement of alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) and beta-human chorionic gonadotropin (beta-hCG). However, the definitive diagnosis and management of a suspected testicular cancer involves surgical intervention.\r\n\r\nThe most accurate and preferred method for diagnosing testicular cancer is **radical inguinal orchidectomy**. This procedure involves the removal of the entire affected testis along with the spermatic cord through an incision in the groin. This approach not only provides tissue for pathological examination to confirm the diagnosis but also minimizes the risk of seeding the cancer cells into the scrotum, which could occur with direct scrotal incision or percutaneous biopsy methods. Radical inguinal orchidectomy serves both a diagnostic and therapeutic role in the management of testicular cancer.","reference":"Agabegi SS, Agabegi ED, Duncan MD, Chuang K. Step-Up to Medicine. 6th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2024: 300.","responses":[{"text":"Percutaneous biopsy of testicular mass","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excisional biopsy of the testicular mass with scrotal incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum level of alpha-fetoprotein and beta human chorionic gonadotropin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radical inguinal orchidectomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Incisional biopsy of testicular mass through a scrotal incision","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21621,"text":"A 10-year-old boy presents to the emergency room with pain In the left testicle. The pain is acute in onset and began 1 hour ago. On physical examination, he has a  high riding, firm, and markedly tender left testis. The right testicle is normal. Urinalysis is unremarkable. Which of the following is the most appropriate management of this patient?","explanation":"The clinical presentation with acute testicular pain, a high-riding, firm, and markedly tender left testis, along with the absence of urinary abnormalities, suggests testicular torsion. This is a surgical emergency where the spermatic cord twists, compromising blood flow to the testicle. **Manual detorsion,** by rotating the testicle **externally** towards the thigh, is the initial step to attempt to restore blood flow. If successful, it can salvage the testicle. However, **orchidopexy** (fixation of the testicle) should follow to prevent future episodes of torsion.\r\n\r\nOrchiectomy (removal of the testicle) would only be considered if the testicle is deemed nonviable after detorsion attempts. Orchidopexy of bilateral testicles is not indicated in this acute scenario, as the right testicle is normal and not involved in the torsion.","reference":"Sharp, Victoria J., et al. “Testicular Torsion: Diagnosis, Evaluation, and Management.” American Family Physician, 15 Dec. 2013, https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2013/1215/p835.html.","responses":[{"text":"Manual detorsion of the left testicle with internal rotation towards the thigh, orchidopexy if the condition recurs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orchidopexy of bilateral testicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orchidopexy of the left testicle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orchiectomy of the left testicle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Manual detorsion of the left testicle with external rotation towards the thigh, orchidopexy if the condition recurs","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21622,"text":"Which one of the following statistical tests Is appropriate for normally distributed continuous data?","explanation":"**Student's t-test** is a parametric test used to compare the means of two groups or samples when the data follows a normal distribution. It is particularly useful when you have continuous data and want to determine if there is a significant difference between the means of two independent groups.\r\n\r\nThis test relies on the assumption of normality in the data distribution and is tailored for continuous variables measured on an interval or ratio scale. Its primary purpose is to compare means between two groups, making it well-suited for evaluating differences in means between datasets with normally distributed continuous data.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Renal-2 Module, Community medicine lecture \" t-test application\".","responses":[{"text":"McNemar’s test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wilcoxon test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chi-square test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levene’s test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Student’s t- test","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21623,"text":"Which of the following sample sizes is appropriate for applying the Z test?","explanation":"The Z test, which is used for hypothesis testing and making inferences about population parameters, requires a sufficiently large sample size to ensure the validity of the statistical analysis. In general, a sample size of **greater than 30** is considered appropriate when using the Z test. This is because larger sample sizes tend to yield more reliable and accurate estimates of population parameters and help in achieving the assumptions of normality and the Central Limit Theorem.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"\u003e30","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"25-30","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003c20","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003c25","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10-15","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21625,"text":"A student has to present the association of liver cancer with five different socioeconomic and demographic variables along with their respective P-values and 95% confidence intervals. Which of the following data presentations would be most suitable for this scenario?","explanation":"**Tables** are excellent for presenting structured data, especially when you need to display multiple variables along with their statistical values. Each variable can be a column, and each row can represent a specific variable's data, including P-values and confidence intervals.\r\n\r\nTables provide a clear and organized way to present numerical information. P-values and confidence intervals can be neatly displayed in their respective cells, making it easy for the audience to locate and compare the values.","reference":"D'26 Lecture slides community medicine lecture,\"Organizing and displaying data.","responses":[{"text":"Simple bar graph","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histogram","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Table","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Line graph","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pie chart","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21626,"text":"You are asked to examine a female suspected of sexual assault. Examination findings reveal a deflorated female. Which of the following defines defloration?","explanation":null,"reference":"Awan NR. Principle and Practice Of Forensic Medicine. 2nd ed. Zubair Book Depot; 2018: 102.","responses":[{"text":"Virginity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post coital bleed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infertility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rape","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loss of virginity","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21627,"text":"You are asked to examine a female suspected of sexual assault. Examination findings reveal a ruptured hymen. What is the most common site of rupture of the hymen in a virgin female?","explanation":null,"reference":"Awan NR. Principle and Practice Of Forensic Medicine. 2nd ed. Zubair Book Depot; 2018: 103.","responses":[{"text":"Anterolateral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterolateral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Traumatic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21628,"text":"What is the type of sexual perversion in which the person gets sexual gratification by inflicting pain on their partner?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 429.","responses":[{"text":"Lesbianism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saddism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bestiality","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masochism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sado-masochism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21629,"text":"Upon taking a detailed history from an offender, it is revealed that he frequently has intercourse with animals. What Is this sexual perversion termed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 427.","responses":[{"text":"Bestiality","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Saddism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesbianism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masochism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21634,"text":"Which of the following statements about the anatomy of the kidneys is correct?","explanation":"Renal columns, also known as **columns of Bertin**, are continuous with the renal cortex and project into the medulla between the renal pyramids. These columns provide structural support to the kidney and contain blood vessels and interlobar arteries.\r\n\r\nIn contrast to the statement that cortical nephrons have lengthier loops of Henle than juxtaglomerular nephrons, it's important to note that juxtamedullary nephrons have longer loops of Henle that extend deep into the renal medulla, while cortical nephrons have shorter loops that do not penetrate as deeply.\r\n\r\nRegarding the caliber of arterioles, typically, the afferent arterioles leading into the glomerulus are wider in diameter than the efferent arterioles.\r\n\r\nMedullary rays are regions within the renal cortex where the nephron tubules and collecting ducts are located, but they do not contain renal corpuscles.\r\n\r\nLastly, vasa recta are specialized capillaries that do extend into the renal medulla, including the renal pyramids, to help regulate the concentration of urine by countercurrent exchange.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Caliber of afferent arterioles is greater than the efferent arterioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortical nephrons have lengthier loops of Henle than the juxtaglomerular nephrons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasa recta are not present in the renal pyramids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medullary rays contain collection of renal corpuscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal columns are the extensions of renal cortex between the adjacent renal pyramids","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21635,"text":"Which of the following statements is correct about the development of the urinary system?","explanation":"In the process of urinary system development, three distinct structures play essential roles: the pronephros, mesonephros, and metanephros. The pronephros and mesonephros are transient structures, while the metanephros forms the permanent kidneys.\r\n\r\nThe **metanephric blastema** that gives rise to various components of the nephron, including the glomerulus, proximal convoluted tubules, distal convoluted tubules, and **loops of Henle.** The loops of Henle are responsible for concentrating urine and maintaining electrolyte balance.\r\n\r\nUreteric buds, originating from the Wolffian duct (mesonephric duct), interact with the metanephric blastema to form the collecting duct system, which includes the calyces, renal pelvis, and ureter. This system transports urine from the nephrons to the bladder.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 598.","responses":[{"text":"Mesonephric tissue is responsible for the formation of permanent kidneys","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metanephric blastema is present at upper thoracic region","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loops of Henle develop from metanephric blastema","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ureteric buds develop into proximal convoluted tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collecting ducts develop from metanephric blastema","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21637,"text":"Every molecule of glucose gets reabsorbed in the proximal convoluted tubule. About 90% of the glucose that is filtered is reabsorbed in the initial segment of the proximal convoluted tubule. Which glucose transporter plays a key role in transporting the majority of glucose from the brush border epithelium into the cell, out of the tubular lumen?","explanation":"**SGLT2** is an essential component of the renal glucose reabsorption process in the proximal convoluted tubule. It works in conjunction with the sodium gradient established by sodium-potassium pumps on the basolateral membrane of the tubular cells. \r\n\r\nAs filtered fluid containing glucose flows through the proximal convoluted tubule, SGLT2 on the brush border epithelium binds to both sodium ions and glucose molecules. The energy derived from sodium moving down its concentration gradient is used to transport glucose against its concentration gradient into the tubular cells. Once inside the tubular cells, glucose can then be transported out of the cells into the interstitial fluid and subsequently into the bloodstream by another transporter known as GLUT2.","reference":"Edward C. Chao; SGLT-2 Inhibitors: A New Mechanism for Glycemic Control. Clin Diabetes 1 January 2014; 32 (1): 4–11. https://doi.org/10.2337/diaclin.32.1.4","responses":[{"text":"Na-Glucose co-transporter 2 (SGLT2)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na-glucose cotransporter 1 (SGLT1)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21638,"text":"In which segment of the renal tubule are the sodium-hydrogen antiporters responsible for hydrogen ion secretion situated?","explanation":"In the **proximal convoluted tubule,** the renal tubular cells contain sodium-hydrogen antiporters, specifically the NHE3 isoform. These antiporters play a crucial role in the reabsorption of sodium ions and the secretion of hydrogen ions. This process is essential for maintaining the body's acid-base balance and regulating the pH of the urine.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 605.","responses":[{"text":"Collecting duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loop of Henle - thin segment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loop of Henle - thick segment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubule","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21639,"text":"During a clinical interview, the doctor asked the patient “What were your feelings when you were talking about a fractured arm you mentioned that you were a physical trainer and could easily lift ten-kilogram weight ten times in a minute”. Asking about emotions and feelings attached to various symptoms and problems in an interview is an example of which of the following?","explanation":"**Selective reflection** is a communication skill that involves reflecting back to the patient their thoughts, feelings, or concerns to confirm understanding and encourage them to explore their emotions further. In this case, the doctor is reflecting the patient's feelings regarding their fractured arm and physical abilities.","reference":"Dow lecture slides \"Communication Skills\", D'26, respiratory-1 module","responses":[{"text":"Funneling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Active listening","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Selective reflection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Empathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Praphrasing","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22648,"text":"A 3-year-old boy presents with fever, dysuria, oliguria, and intense pain in the abdomen. Physical examination shows a prominent suprapubic area which is dull on percussion. Urinalysis reveals red blood cells but no proteinuria. A diagnosis of hydronephrosis was made. What is the important morphological feature of hydronephrosis?","explanation":"Hydronephrosis is characterized by the **dilation of the renal pelvis and calyces** of a kidney, often leading to the **progressive atrophy of the renal parenchyma** due to obstructed urine outflow. This condition results from the accumulation of urine in the kidney due to obstruction in the urinary tract, which can occur at any level from the renal pelvis to the urethral meatus. The sustained pressure from urine accumulation leads to the dilation of the renal pelvis and calyces, and if the obstruction persists, it eventually causes compression and damage to the kidney's functional tissue, the parenchyma. This damage can lead to impaired kidney function and renal failure if left untreated.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 946.","responses":[{"text":"Cortical scarring and shrinking caused by thickening and hyalinization of the vessel walls","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortical tubulointerstitial damage with small contracted kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enlarged kidneys with multiple cysts in the cortex and medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilatation of renal calyces and pelvis with atrophy of renal parenchyma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Patchy interstitial suppurative inflammation, intratubular aggregates of neutrophilic tubulitis, and tubular necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22649,"text":"An 8-month-old infant was diagnosed with autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease. Which one of the following other abnormalities can develop in this patient?","explanation":"**Congenital hepatic fibrosis** is a condition commonly associated with ARPKD. Congenital hepatic fibrosis is characterized by the fibrosis and the formation of cysts within the liver. It arises due to the developmental defect of the ductal plate, the embryonic structure that eventually forms the bile ducts in the liver. This condition can lead to complications such as portal hypertension and is a significant feature of the hepatic involvement in ARPKD.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 943.","responses":[{"text":"Retinal dystrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracranial berry aneurysm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polycystic liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic cysts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital hepatic fibrosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22650,"text":"Which of the following statements are false regarding the etiology and pathogenesis of pyelonephritis and urinary tract infection?","explanation":"In reality, pyelonephritis and UTIs are more common in females than in males, primarily due to anatomical differences, such as the shorter urethra in females, which allows easier bacterial ascent from the external environment to the bladder and potentially to the kidneys. The most common causative agent indeed is Escherichia coli (E. coli), a gram-negative bacillus. These infections can occur due to ascending infection from the bladder (most common route) or through hematogenous dissemination. The fact that these conditions are more prevalent in females is well-documented, making the **statement regarding higher prevalence in males incorrect.**","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 927.","responses":[{"text":"It is more common in males","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Caused by gram-negative bacilli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The most common causative agent is E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is more common in females","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It can be caused by ascending infection from the bladder or through hematogenous dissemination","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22651,"text":"A 45-year-old woman has angina pectoris, polyuria, and polydipsia for the past 5 years. On physical examination, she has a body mass index (BMI) of 32 kg/m². Laboratory studies show an HbA1C of 10%. Urinalysis shows macroalbuminuria, with no ketonuria. Which one of the following morphological changes can be attributed to the patient's proteinuria?","explanation":"The patient's clinical profile, characterized by long-standing poorly controlled diabetes (evidenced by high HbA1C levels), obesity (BMI of 32 kg/m²), and macroalbuminuria, is indicative of diabetic nephropathy, a common complication of diabetes mellitus. In diabetic nephropathy, several morphological changes can occur within the kidneys, but the hallmark change linked to the onset of proteinuria (albuminuria) is **glomerular basement membrane thickening**.\r\n\r\nThis thickening is a result of the accumulation of extracellular matrix components and is one of the earliest histopathological changes observed in diabetic nephropathy. It contributes to the altered glomerular filtration barrier, leading to the leakage of proteins, especially albumin, into the urine. While other changes like nodular glomerulosclerosis (Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules), papillary necrosis, tubular basement membrane thickening, and hyaline arteriosclerosis are also associated with diabetic nephropathy, it's the glomerular basement membrane thickening that is closely associated with the proteinuria seen in this patient.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1110.","responses":[{"text":"Hyaline arteriosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Papillary necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomerular basement membrane thickening","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nodular glomerulosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tubular basement membrane thickening","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22653,"text":"A clinical study is performed on laboratory findings in subjects with renal diseases. Loss of physiologic function accompanies many diseases. Loss of which of the following renal functions is most likely to be identified by laboratory measurement of the urine-specific gravity following water deprivation?","explanation":"The ability of the kidneys to **concentrate** urine is a vital aspect of renal function, crucial for maintaining body fluid homeostasis. When assessing renal function through laboratory measurements, the measurement of urine-specific gravity following water deprivation is primarily indicative of the kidney's **concentration** ability. Urine-specific gravity reflects the density of urine compared to water, and it's a measure of the concentration of solutes present in the urine. \r\n\r\nIn a water deprivation state, healthy kidneys should be able to concentrate urine effectively, leading to an increase in urine-specific gravity due to the reabsorption of water in the renal tubules. This process is largely regulated by the hormone vasopressin (antidiuretic hormone, ADH), which promotes water reabsorption in the collecting ducts of the kidneys. A failure to adequately concentrate urine, noted by a relatively low or unchanging specific gravity following water deprivation, may suggest impaired renal tubular function or an issue with ADH action or production, highlighting potential renal dysfunction.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 374.","responses":[{"text":"Reabsorption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Concentration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Filtration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood flow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22654,"text":"A 5-year-old boy presents with generalized and periorbital edema. Further investigations show hypoalbuminemia, lipiduria, and 3.74 g proteinuria. Which of the following conditions is the most likely cause in this patient?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of generalized and periorbital edema, hypoalbuminemia, lipiduria, and significant proteinuria in this boy is highly indicative of **Minimal Change Disease** (MCD). MCD is the most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children and is characterized by the loss of significant amounts of protein in the urine, leading to low levels of protein in the blood (hypoalbuminemia), high levels of fat and cholesterol in the blood (hyperlipidemia), and swelling (edema).\r\n\r\nThe name \"minimal change\" comes from the fact that the glomeruli, or filtering units of the kidney, appear almost normal when examined under a light microscope. The diagnosis is often confirmed by the absence of significant changes in kidney tissue, although foot process effacement of podocytes is observed under electron microscopy. The cause of MCD is not fully understood but is believed to involve immune system dysfunction. The condition responds well to corticosteroids, which can induce remission of proteinuria and resolution of edema.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 914.","responses":[{"text":"IgA nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Minimal Change Disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Amyloidosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22655,"text":"Nephrotic syndrome is a clinical complex characterized by massive proteinuria of 3.5 gm or more of protein loss per 24 hours, hypoalbuminemia, generalized edema, hyperlipidemia, and lipiduria. Which of the following causes of nephrotic syndrome is steroid-responsive?","explanation":"**Minimal change nephrotic syndrome** (MCNS) also known as nil disease, is the most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children but can also occur in adults. The characteristic feature of this condition is the minimal or no change observed in the glomeruli under light microscopy, while electron microscopy reveals effacement of the foot processes of podocytes.\r\n\r\nPatients with MCNS typically respond well to corticosteroid therapy, leading to remission of proteinuria and resolution of edema. The exact mechanism by which steroids work in MCNS is not entirely clear, but they are thought to stabilize the podocyte cytoskeleton, reduce protein leakage through the glomerular filtration barrier, and possibly modulate immune responses. Despite the good initial response to steroids, relapses are common in MCNS, and long-term management may require other immunosuppressive medications.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 914.","responses":[{"text":"FSGS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Minimal change nephrotic syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Finnish type of congenital NS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22656,"text":"A 30-year-old man complains of puffiness around his eyes and swelling of his feet for 2 weeks. On examination, his blood pressure is 155/95 mm Hg. Urine microscopic examination reveals oval fat bodies. Which of the following conditions is he most likely to have?","explanation":"**Nephrotic syndrome** condition is characterized by a set of symptoms including severe proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, hyperlipidemia, and edema. The presence of oval fat bodies in the urine, also known as \"maltese cross\" formations under polarized light, is a classic sign of nephrotic syndrome. These structures are lipid-laden renal tubular cells or free fat droplets, often seen in conditions where there is significant protein and lipid loss in the urine due to increased glomerular permeability.\r\n\r\nThe patient's hypertension, along with the periorbital puffiness (commonly seen in nephrotic syndrome due to fluid retention) and lower extremity edema, further supports this diagnosis. Nephrotic syndrome can have various underlying causes, including primary glomerular diseases or secondary conditions affecting the kidneys.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 911.","responses":[{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascending pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive uropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephritic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal infarction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22657,"text":"Tubulointerstitial nephritis is inflammation that affects the tubules and the tissue surrounding them called \"Interstitial tissue.\" The onset of tubulointerstitial nephritis may be acute (sudden) or chronic (gradual) and often results in kidney failure. Which of the following is the most common cause of acute tubulointerstitial nephritis?","explanation":"The most common cause of acute tubulointerstitial nephritis is an **allergic drug reaction**. This type of kidney inflammation often occurs in response to certain medications. The body's immune system mistakenly identifies the drug as a harmful substance and mounts an immune response against the kidney's tubules and surrounding interstitial tissue.","reference":"Tubulointerstitial nephritis - kidney and urinary tract disorders. MSD Manual Consumer Version. Accessed January 12, 2024. https://www.msdmanuals.com/home/kidney-and-urinary-tract-disorders/kidney-filtering-disorders/tubulointerstitial-nephritis","responses":[{"text":"Heavy metal toxins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urate nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Allergic drug reaction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Certain types of blood cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Damage from a drug (not an allergic reaction)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22658,"text":"A 32-year-old case of diabetes mellitus and using alcohol occasionally, presented with loose stools, watery in consistency for 3 days. He has around 10-12 of these episodes every day. On examination, he was dehydrated, with around 200 ml of urine output in 24 hours. Initial investigation showed an Hb of 14.8 mg/dL, TLC 11.2 x 10³/L, platelet count of 324x 10³/L, K⁺ 9.4 mEq/L, HCO₃⁻ 18, Urea: 94. Among the mentioned laboratory parameters which of the following is a highly indicative marker for hemodialysis?","explanation":"Hyperkalemia is a potentially life-threatening electrolyte disturbance and can lead to serious cardiac dysrhythmias or arrest. In situations where the **potassium** level is critically high, urgent treatment is required.\r\n\r\nWhile elevated urea and reduced urine output are also concerning and indicative of kidney dysfunction, they are not as immediately life-threatening as severe hyperkalemia. The body's acid-base balance, indicated by bicarbonate levels, is also crucial, but the potassium level in this scenario poses the most urgent risk. Therefore, immediate intervention, often in the form of hemodialysis, is critical to reduce the potassium level and mitigate the risk of cardiac complications.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 422.","responses":[{"text":"Urine output","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creatinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicarbonate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22659,"text":"A 24-year-old female presented with decreased urination and hematuria for 2 days. She has been unwell for the past 15 days with a severe sore throat and high-grade fever with chills. On examination, she has a blood pressure of 150/100 mmHg, pulse of 94/min, and temperature of 100°F. Systemic and general physical examinations were unremarkable. Which of the following urinary casts is most specific for her illness?","explanation":"The patient's presentation of hematuria, decreased urination, high blood pressure, and a recent history of a sore throat with fever suggests a post-infectious glomerulonephritis, typically following a streptococcal infection. The urinary cast type that is most specific and indicative of this condition is the **red cell cast**.\r\n\r\nRed cell casts in the urine are highly suggestive of glomerular disease, where red blood cells leak into the urine due to damage to the glomerular capillaries. This is commonly seen in acute glomerulonephritis, which can be a complication following infections like strep throat. The presence of red cell casts implies that the source of the blood is from the glomeruli and not from lower in the urinary tract.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 392, 401.","responses":[{"text":"Granular casts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaline casts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epithelial casts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"White cell casts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red cell casts","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22660,"text":"A 50-year-old male is admitted to the medical ward with a history of abdominal distention and pedal edema. He is diagnosed as a case of chronic liver disease (cirrhosis). A complete blood count (CBC) shows a Hb of 10 mg/dL, WBC 3x10 mm³, platelet count 105x10 mm³, serum albumin 2.7mg/dl, prothrombin time 18 sec, (normal: 11-14 sec). Serum sodium is 122 mEq/L, serum K⁺ 3.6 mg/L, creatinine 1.1 mg/dl. What is the cause of hyponatremia in this patient according to history and physical examination?","explanation":"The patient's presentation and laboratory findings are indicative of chronic liver disease, characterized by abdominal distention (likely due to ascites), pedal edema, low serum albumin, prolonged prothrombin time, and thrombocytopenia. The hyponatremia observed in this patient, with a serum sodium level of 122 mEq/L, is most likely due to **hypotonic hypervolumic hyponatremia**.\r\n\r\nIn chronic liver disease, especially cirrhosis, there's a reduction in the effective circulating blood volume. Despite the total body water being increased (mainly because of fluid retention and ascites), the body perceives a state of hypovolemia due to the vasodilatation in the splanchnic circulation. This stimulates the secretion of antidiuretic hormone (ADH), leading to water retention and dilutional hyponatremia. This condition is termed hypervolemic hyponatremia because total body water is increased, even though the effective circulating volume is perceived as low by the body. It's also hypotonic because the osmolality of the serum is low due to excess water relative to sodium.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 354, 357.","responses":[{"text":"Hypotonic hypervolumic hyponatremia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertonic hyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypotonic euvolumic hyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudohyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypotonic hypovolemic hyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22661,"text":"A 60-year-old male known diabetic for 8 years, taking oral hypoglycemic drugs is admitted to the medical intensive care unit (ICU) with an altered level of consciousness. There is no history of fever. There are no signs of meningeal irritation. Investigation: complete blood count (CBC) 11 mg/dL, WBC 5X10⁹ mm³, platelet count of 162 x10⁹ mm³. Random blood sugar (RBS) of 590 mg/dL, creatinine 1.2 mg/dL, serum sodium 168mg/dL, and a serum potassium of 3.9 mg/dl. For treating this patient, which of the following should not be given at this time to correct metabolic and electrolyte problems?","explanation":"The patient is presenting with severe hyperglycemia and hypernatremia, which are indicative of a hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state, a serious complication of diabetes that requires immediate medical attention. The patient's altered level of consciousness suggests a significant disturbance in his metabolic status.\r\n\r\nGiven the patient's high serum sodium level (168 mg/dL), **hypertonic saline** should not be administered at this time. Administering hypertonic saline would exacerbate the hypernatremia and increase the risk of further complications, including central pontine myelinolysis. The primary goal in managing hypernatremia is careful correction of the sodium imbalance. This is typically achieved with the administration of isotonic or hypotonic fluids, such as normal saline or half-strength saline, respectively. These fluids help to lower the serum sodium concentration gradually, avoiding rapid shifts that could lead to cerebral edema.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, regular insulin is essential to address the hyperglycemia and to facilitate the transport of glucose into cells. However, it's crucial to monitor the patient's potassium levels because insulin administration can lead to hypokalemia, necessitating careful monitoring and supplementation if required.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 360.","responses":[{"text":"Half Strength Saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ringer Lactate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertonic saline","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Regular insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal saline","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22662,"text":"A 55-year-old male patient with poorly controlled diabetes mellitus presented with high-grade fever with chills, loin pain \u0026 tenderness over kidneys. His ultrasound shows hydroureter and hydronephrosis on the right side. What is the most appropriate management?","explanation":"The patient is showing symptoms indicative of a serious urinary tract infection, possibly complicated by obstruction, as evidenced by hydroureter and hydronephrosis seen on ultrasound. This situation is particularly concerning given the patient's status as a poorly controlled diabetic, which can impair immune function and complicate infections. \r\n\r\nThe most appropriate management in this case is to **admit the patient, provide intravenous (IV) antibiotics, and facilitate drainage by percutaneous nephrostomy**. This approach tackles both the infection and the obstruction. Immediate antibiotic therapy is crucial to manage the infection, and the obstruction must be relieved to restore urine flow and prevent further complications. Delaying intervention or opting for less aggressive treatment, like outpatient management or oral antibiotics, might put the patient at risk for worsening infection, sepsis, or irreversible kidney damage. A multidisciplinary team involving urologists and infectious disease specialists would ideally manage the patient's care to address these complex issues comprehensively.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 413-414.","responses":[{"text":"Surgical nephrectomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Should be given I/V antibiotics empirically","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Can be managed as outpatient on oral antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Should be admitted given I/V antibiotics and drainage by percutaneous nephrostomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Should be given I/V fluids \u0026 cranberry juice","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22663,"text":"A 25-year-old pregnant female is advised a urine analysis and urine culture at 12 weeks of gestation. Which one of the following is correct regarding asymptomatic bacteriuria?","explanation":"In the context of asymptomatic bacteriuria, especially during pregnancy, the diagnosis is  significant when there are **more than 10⁵ organisms/ml** of a single urinary pathogen in the absence of symptoms. Asymptomatic bacteriuria is a condition where bacteria are present in the urine but without the patient experiencing any related symptoms. This condition is quite common during pregnancy and requires attention because if left untreated, it may lead to more severe complications like pyelonephritis, which can pose risks to both the mother and the fetus.\r\n\r\nThe threshold of more than 10⁵ organisms/ml is used as a diagnostic criterion because it helps distinguish between true infection and contamination from the external genitalia or distal urethra, especially in midstream urine samples. Therefore, in clinical practice, the presence of more than 10⁵ colony-forming units per milliliter (CFU/mL) of the same bacteria in two consecutive urine samples from a woman with no symptoms of urinary tract infection is considered diagnostic of asymptomatic bacteriuria in pregnant women.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 428-429.","responses":[{"text":"More than 10³ organisms/ml is regarded as significant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal urine culture does not exclude asymptomatic bacteriuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"More than 10⁵ organisms/ml is regarded as significant","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Any number of organisms is regarded as significant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Up to 10 organisms/ml is considered diagnostic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22664,"text":"A 49-year-old male known diabetic, went for a follow-up renal check-up and reports an eGFR of 36ml/min/1.73 m². He was carrying his report from 4 months back, showing Urea: 78 mg/dL, serum creatinine 2.3 mg/dL, eGFR was 38 ml/min/1.73 m², and albumin: creatinine ratio was 300 mg/g. What will be the stage of his disease?","explanation":"CKD is categorized into different stages based on the glomerular filtration rate (GFR), a measure of how well the kidneys are filtering waste from the blood. In this case, the patient's estimated GFR (eGFR) is 36 ml/min/1.73 m². According to the guidelines, CKD is staged as follows:\r\n\r\nStage 1: eGFR ≥90 ml/min/1.73 m² with signs of kidney damage (e.g., proteinuria)\r\nStage 2: eGFR 60–89 ml/min/1.73 m² with signs of kidney damage\r\nStage 3a: eGFR 45–59 ml/min/1.73 m²\r\n**Stage 3b: eGFR 30–44 ml/min/1.73 m²**\r\nStage 4: eGFR 15–29 ml/min/1.73 m²\r\nStage 5: eGFR \u003c15 ml/min/1.73 m² or on dialysis\r\n\r\nGiven that the patient's eGFR lies between 30 and 44 ml/min/1.73 m² and considering the presence of other factors like an elevated albumin: creatinine ratio indicating kidney damage, the diagnosis aligns with Stage 3b CKD. This stage is characterized by moderately to severely decreased kidney function, and patients are at an increased risk of complications related to kidney disease and cardiovascular events.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Renal and Excretory Module. Subject: Medicine, Topic: Chronic Kidney Disease, Sub-topic: Staging of CKD.","responses":[{"text":"Stage 3b chronic kidney disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 2 chronic kidney disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 3a chronic kidney disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 4 chronic kidney disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 5 chronic kidney disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22665,"text":"A 50-year-old male, a known case of diabetes mellitus and hypertension comes to the emergency department with complaints of decreased appetite, easy fatigability, and progressive shortness of breath for the last 4-5 months. On examination, blood pressure was 165/90 mm of Hg, pulse 85 beats/min, and respiratory rate 26/min. He appears pale, with periorbital puffiness and bilateral pedal edema present. Lab parameters show an Hb of 8.0 mg/dL, a normal TLC and platelet count, BUN was 60, and serum creatinine was 3.2 mg/dL. Potassium was also high. An 8-month-old report showed the same levels of deranged renal parameters. What will be the best possible diagnosis?","explanation":"The patient's presentation suggests a state of **chronic renal failure**, also known as chronic kidney disease (CKD). CKD is characterized by a gradual and irreversible deterioration of renal function over time. In this case, the patient has a history of two major risk factors for CKD: diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Both conditions can lead to the progressive damage of the kidneys through mechanisms such as glomerulosclerosis and nephroangiosclerosis.\r\n\r\nThe presence of persistent symptoms like decreased appetite, fatigue, and shortness of breath, alongside clinical findings such as hypertension, periorbital puffiness, and bilateral pedal edema, are indicative of volume overload, a common manifestation of advanced CKD. The presence of anemia (Hb 8.0 mg/dL) is a common complication of CKD due to decreased erythropoietin production by the kidneys. Elevated BUN and creatinine levels signify impaired kidney function, and hyperkalemia (high potassium) is typical due to decreased excretion by the kidneys. Most importantly, the persistence of these deranged renal parameters over 8 months rules out acute conditions and firmly points towards chronic renal failure.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 415.","responses":[{"text":"Acute glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute on chronic renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic renal failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute tubular necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

